{"lookup_validation":"0","name":"Communications and Language Assessment","remove_margins":"","setPaperType":"us","content":"
Taxi driver communication and language assessment 
 
Licensed drivers in Rugby should provide members of the public with a high quality service. To help achieve this all drivers are expected to have the necessary communication and language skills in order to communicate effectively with passengers. 
 
All new applicants to Rugby Borough Council for driver licences are required to pass a communication and language assessment which is carried out on the Council’s behalf by the Adult and Community Learning team (ACL). 
 
The fee is £10 which is paid direct (by cash or cheque) to the ACL when you attend for the assessment. When you attend, you must also bring some photographic identification such as a current passport for example.  Please note that you must first submit your driver’s licence application to the Council before booking your assessment. 
 
The assessment takes place at the ACL office located at the Bloxham Centre, Somers Road, Rugby CV22 7DE. Please call them on 01788 552933 to book. If you are unable to attend an appointment you must give ACL a minimum of 24 hours’ notice of cancellation or you will be required to pay a further fee.  
 
The assessment is done on a one-to-one basis and applicants will provide most of their answers verbally. There are also a number of questions with multiple-choice answers. The questions are linked to the role of a taxi driver, and the assessment consists of the following sections;
Vocabulary - you will be asked to name a number of various objects from several pictures and photographs;
Money matters - there are around 10 questions (mainly with multiple choice answers) designed to assess that you are familiar with numbers, and that you have an understanding of phrases and terms relating to money;
Directions - you will be asked to look at a map of an area and to show that you can understand and follow directions to a number of locations on the map;
Places - you will be shown a number of photographs and be asked to identify various places shown on  them;
Phrases and meanings - this section covers various phrases and words linked to driving a taxi and you will be asked to show that you understand these phrases and words (around 12 questions). 
The results of the assessment will be given to you straight afterwards. If you fail the assessment then you can arrange a re-sit with the ACL. Applicants who fail will be given the opportunity to receive support from ACL to develop communication and language skills - this support is optional and costs £25 per hour.  ACL can discuss this with you in the event that you do not pass the assessment.
If you have any questions regarding this assessment please contact the Council on 01788 533533
For the purposes of this assessment the term ‘taxi’ refers to either a licensed hackney carriage or a private hire vehicle.
"}

Further to your request, I am pleased to send you a Blue Badge application form and guidance notes. Please complete all relevant sections of the form.

You will also need to submit the following with your completed application:

One recent passport type/size photograph of yourself with your name in capital letters and your signature on the back.

An application fee of £10. Please send a cheque or postal order for £10 payable to “Warwickshire County Council”. Payment will only be taken if the application is successful.   • receives the higher rate mobility component of Disability Living Allowance.
  • receives a War Pensioner’s Mobility Supplement.
  • receives a Personal Independence Payment (PIP) with a moving around descriptor of 8 points or more.
  • is a registered blind person under the National Assistance Act 1948.
  • has been awarded a benefit (giving rise to a lump sum at tariffs 1-8 inclusive) under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) and has also been certified by the Service Personnel and Veterans agency as having a permanent and substantial disability which causes inability to walk or very considerable difficulty in walking.

Eligible following assessment

Those who do not meet one of the criterion above, but meet one of the following criterion, may be eligible for a Blue Badge:

  • has a severe disability in both upper limbs, regularly drives a motor vehicle, but has difficulty operating parking meters.
  • has a permanent and substantial disability which means you are unable to walk or have very considerable difficulty in walking.
  • children under 3 years of age who, because of a specific medical condition, needs to travel with bulky medical equipment or needs to be close to a vehicle for emergency medical treatment.

As part of the assessment process, it may be necessary to invite you for a face-to-face assessment.

A face-to-face assessment usually takes 45 minutes, but may take longer if it is complex. You will need to bring proof of prescriptions, photographic proof of identification and your usual walking aids.

Upon receipt of the above documentation we will consider your eligibility for a blue badge.

If you require any further assistance please contact us again at the above address or contact number and we will be pleased to help you.

Rugby Open 2017
December 2017 - January 2018
 

 

Call for entries of visual art and craft for our annual Open exhibition at Rugby Art Gallery and Museum.

 

Eligibility (Members of the selection panel are not eligible to enter)

Artists and makers aged 16 or over on the date of submission (19 November  2017) are eligible who comply with one of the following criteria:

  • Members of one of the following established Rugby Artist groups; Alchemy, Rugby and District Art Society, Dunchurch Photographic Society, The Tantalus Project, Rugby Artists'  Group.
  • Currently studying or have studied in the Rugby Borough.
  • Live or occupy a studio within a 15 mile radius of Rugby Art Gallery and Museum including the following villages: Allesley, Astley, Blaby, Burton Green, Chapel Brampton, Church Brampton, Corley Ash, Corley Morr, East Farndon, Enderby, Fenny Compton, Fleckney, Gumley, Harpole, Heyford, Higham on the Hill, Kelmarsh, Kilby, Lubernham, Narborough, Stapleton, Stockingford, Stoke Golding, Thurlaston, Upper Stowe, Whetstone, Woodford Halse.

 

Entry

Up to three original artworks created in the last year can be entered per applicant.  Entries will be accepted in the form of painting, sculpture, drawing, print, photography, film/video and craft.  Performance and installation cannot be accepted.  Selected works must remain on display in the Art Gallery up to and including the 13th January 2018.

 

Entry Fee

A fee of £5.00 per work (or £12.00 for three works by the same artist) is payable following submission of the application form.  This fee is to cover exhibition administration and is non-refundable.

 

Selection Panel

Elected Council Members, a representative from local art group and Michael Shaw (curator of ‘Sculpting the Museum’. The panel’s decision is final.

                                                                                                                                                        

Prizes to be announced at the preview

First prize supported by Rugby Borough Council: cash prize and an exhibition in Floor One Gallery.

RAGM People’s Choice Award of £100 for the most popular choice voted for by the public.  This year we are launching the Martin Valentine Prize for Promising Young Artists (16 - 24yrs), supported in partnership with The Fosse House Gallery, Dunchurch.  More prizes to be announced.

 

Publicity & Display of Work

The Gallery reserves the right to photograph exhibits for education and publicity purposes including social media. Copyright will be acknowledged in appropriate cases. The Art Gallery’s decision on the display of the work is final.

 

 

Artwork insurance

Works are submitted for selection at the owner’s risk.  The works will be kept securely and handled with due professional care, but neither the Art Gallery, the Council or its employees accepts liability for loss or damage during the storage, selection periods and exhibition, unless loss or damage is caused by negligence of the Art Gallery, the Council or its employees.

 

Sale of Artwork

Work entered into the exhibition may be for sale.  The gallery will take a 25% commission (+VAT on commission) on any works sold during the exhibition.  Please indicate on the application form if work is for sale and note the retail price or insurance value as applicable.  Note: You need to put approximately 43% onto your original asking price to cover these costs.  Sales cheques will be issued during Feb 2018.

 

e.g.    Original asking price                                        £35.00

          plus asking price x 43 %                                  £15.05

          Selling price                                                    £50.05

 

e.g.    Selling price                                                    £50.00

          minus Commission (25%)                                £12.50  

          minus VAT on Commission (20%)                    £ 2.50

          Amount payable to Artist                                  £35.00

 

SUBMISSION PROCEDURE & CONDITIONS OF ENTRY

Please read this before submitting your Application Form.

 

  1. SIZE & WEIGHT OF WORK

All two-dimensional and three-dimensional work should measure a maximum of 150cm in any direction (including diagonally) should be submitted in person on Sunday 19 November 10 – 4 pm.  The work must be able to be carried by one person and be less than 25 kilos in weight.

 

Please measure your work before delivering it, as over-size works will be turned away, as will paintings with WET PAINT!

 

  1. TOP OF WORK

Each work must be marked ‘TOP’ on the back to show which way up it goes.

 

  1. LABELS

ONE TIE ON LABEL, on a length of string that will hang over the front of the work, AND ONE STICK ON LABEL must be put on each work detailing artist’s name, title of work, medium and selling price.

 

  1. MIRROR PLATES


For security reasons all two-dimensional work MUST BE MIRROR PLATED on the vertical sides.  (Mirror plates can be obtained from art shops, DIY stores and most hardware shops, see illustration below).

All works should be delivered framed or otherwise ready to hang with mirror plates only, not cord.  Clip frames are not acceptable. 

 

  1. FRAMES

Rugby Art Gallery and Museum will handle all artwork with care, however we cannot accept responsibility for any damage to the frame. 

If you feel your work is of a particularly delicate nature please point this out to the staff when submitting your art work, and please provide suitable protection to the artwork if considered  necessary  e.g. corner protection. Any protection should not impede the view of the artwork.

 

NOTE: Please carefully consider the framing/presentation your work.  Art works have been rejected due to poor quality presentation.

 

 

Delivery and collection of artworks – special circumstances

The entrant is responsible for delivery and collection of their artworks, whether or not the entry is exhibited.  If delivery/collection is entrusted to someone else, he or she must bring a letter of authority from the artist, whose signature matches the one on the Application Form.

If you are unable to collect your works during the collection periods outlined, alternative arrangements must be made in advance of the collection dates with Art Gallery staff.

A charge of £1 per day to a maximum of £10 per work will be made for works not collected  on the stated dates.  Please note this is a storage charge and that no exceptions can be made.  The Gallery reserves the right to dispose of any work not collected by 31st January 2018.

Dear {ApplicantTitle} {ApplicantFirstName} {ApplicantSurname}

Further to your request, I am pleased to send you a Blue Badge application form and guidance notes. Please complete all relevant sections of the form.

You will also need to submit the following with your completed application:

One recent passport type/size photograph of yourself with your name in capital letters and your signature on the back.

An application fee of £10. Please send a cheque or postal order for £10 payable to “Warwickshire County Council”. Payment will only be taken if the application is successful. (If you pay by postal order we recommend that you keep your receipt, as you will require this to obtain a refund of the £10 from your post office if the postal order is returned to you).

Eligible without further assessment.

Anyone who meets one of the following criteria is eligible for the issue of a Blue Badge without further assessment. Please provide the original uprating entitlement letter:

  • receives the higher rate mobility component of Disability Living Allowance.
  • receives a War Pensioner’s Mobility Supplement.
  • receives a Personal Independence Payment (PIP) with a moving around descriptor of 8 points or more.
  • is a registered blind person under the National Assistance Act 1948.
  • has been awarded a benefit (giving rise to a lump sum at tariffs 1-8 inclusive) under the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) and has also been certified by the Service Personnel and Veterans agency as having a permanent and substantial disability which causes inability to walk or very considerable difficulty in walking.

Eligible following assessment

Those who do not meet one of the criterion above, but meet one of the following criterion, may be eligible for a Blue Badge:

  • has a severe disability in both upper limbs, regularly drives a motor vehicle, but has difficulty operating parking meters.
  • has a permanent and substantial disability which means you are unable to walk or have very considerable difficulty in walking.
  • children under 3 years of age who, because of a specific medical condition, needs to travel with bulky medical equipment or needs to be close to a vehicle for emergency medical treatment.

As part of the assessment process, it may be necessary to invite you for a face-to-face assessment.

A face-to-face assessment usually takes 45 minutes, but may take longer if it is complex. You will need to bring proof of prescriptions, photographic proof of identification and your usual walking aids.

Upon receipt of the above documentation we will consider your eligibility for a blue badge.

If you require any further assistance please contact us again at the above address or contact number and we will be pleased to help you.

    These terms and conditions govern the Agreement between Warwickshire County Council ('we', 'our' or 'us') and the person making a research request ('you' or 'your').
Who we are
Warwickshire County Record Office (CRO) is a part of Warwickshire County Council.
Our research service
We offer a research service for those unable to visit the office in person and whose enquiries will require more than 15 minutes of research.
Our research is carried out by our own experienced researcher with over 10 years' experience and an in-depth knowledge of the record office holdings.
We are able to carry out research into many of the records held at the County Record Office, which include:
Parish registers and records
Records of nonconformity
Census returns for Warwickshire, 1841-1901
General Register Office indexes of births, marriages and deaths, 1837-1983
Family Search and the IGI
National Burial Index
Newspapers and a range of on-line sources, such as Ancestry.com
As part of your initial enquiry it is important that you state clearly what records you would like us to search for you and what you hope to find out. It is also important to include any information that you already have which might help us in our search. We cannot, of course, guarantee that in every case the answer will be found.
We aim to perform the research requested within 30 days of receiving a research service request. If for some reason, it is not possible to perform the research requested within three months, we will advise you accordingly as soon as possible and provide you with a full refund if requested.
Charges
The research fee for this service is £30.00 (inclusive of VAT) per hour. This includes the cost of delivery where applicable.
The research fee of £30.00 is our minimum charge, i.e. where a search takes less than an hour to complete, the charge for the search will still be £30.00.
We will complete as much of the research you have requested that we can carry out as the time paid for allows.
Once we have carried out you research request, we may be able to suggest further lines of research.
How to cancel
You have the right to cancel your research request within seven working days from the day after you submit your research request e.g. if you submit your research request on Monday the 7th, you will have until Wednesday the 16th to notify us that you wish to cancel your research request. This is the cancellation period. We will not begin any requested research until the cancellation period has expired.
If you wish to cancel your request during the cancellation period, please let us know in writing, via post, fax or e-mail. The cancellation will be effective from the date you notify us of your wish to cancel your request. On receiving notice of your wish to cancel your request, we will arrange for a full refund to be made to you as soon as possible, and in any case, within 30 days of cancellation.
